
Day 7/30 — Week 1 report . Grading myself publicly.
No highlights reel. Just the truth.
Monday I said ChatGPT is an agent.
By Friday  I understood why that statement is embarrassing.
Mindset shift: 10/10
The thing nobody tells you about agents:
It's not about AI.
It's about architecture.
LLM is just one piece. Tools. Memory. Loop. Wallet.
Remove any one of those — you don't have an agent. You have an expensive autocomplete.
Hardest thing I wrote this week:
The ReAct loop post.
Not because it's complex.
Because I had to explain it without using a single technical term —
and still make a Solidity dev go "oh. I've literally written that before."
Took 4 rewrites.
Moment that actually hit different:
Writing 20 lines of Python —
and watching it think out loud before acting.
It didn't just call the function. It said "I need the ETH price. I have a tool for that. Let me use it."
First time I felt like I was watching a junior dev — not running a script.
That moment changed how I see agents completely.
What the comments taught me this week:
Most developers know about agents.
Almost nobody can explain what makes something an agent vs a chatbot.
That gap? That's exactly why this series exists.
One thing I got wrong this week:
I thought the hardest part of agents was the AI.
It's not.
It's the infrastructure underneath.
Who holds the wallet? Who pays the gas? Who stops it if it goes rogue?
That's what Week 2 is entirely about.
And if you're a Solidity dev you're going to feel very at home
.
Week 2 starts tomorrow.
We go from "what is an agent" to "why agents will break without a blockchain."
The real series starts now.
